statement.p:
Which of the following functions are exponential functions, and which are power functions?

F(x) = 1.5^x

G(x) = 3x^{1.5}

H(x) = 3^{1.5x}

K(x) = (3x)^{1.5}

ol.li:
We write each factor as a power of 3.
3^3 \cdot 3^{-2x} \amp= \left(3^2\right)^{x+1}\amp\amp\blert{27=3^3~\text{and}~9=3^2.}
We use the laws of exponents to simplify each side: 3^{3-2x} = 3^{2x+2} Now we equate the exponents to obtain 3 - 2x \amp = 2x + 2 -4x =\amp -1 The solution is x = \dfrac{1}{4}.

li.p:
We let P represent the number of fleas present after t days. The original population of 10 fleas doubles not every day, but every 5 days. A table of values for P would look like this.
t P(t) \hphantom{0000}
0 10 \hphantom{0000}
5 20 P(\alert{5}) = 10 \cdot 2^{\alert{1}} = 20
10 40 P(\alert{10}) = 10 \cdot 2^{\alert{2}} = 40
15 80 P(\alert{15}) = 10 \cdot 2^{\alert{3}} = 80
20 160 P(\alert{20}) = 10 \cdot 2^{\alert{4}} = 160
Notice that the original population is multiplied by another factor of 2 every 5 days. We must divide t by 5 to see how many times the population doubles. The formula for P is thus P(t) = 10 \cdot 2^{t/5}

ol.li:
We set P = \alert{10,240} and solve for t:
		\alert{10,240} \amp = 10\cdot 2^{t/5}\amp\amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by 10.}}
			1024 \amp = 2^{t/5} \amp\amp \blert{\text {Write 1024 as a power of 2.}}
			2^{10} \amp = 2^{t/5}
	We equate the exponents to get 10 = \dfrac{t}{5}, or t = 50. The population will grow to 10,240 fleas in 50 days.

